  "doc_id": "18564",
  "text": "Using the Cluster-Chip, we determined that CTC clusters are heterogeneous, including both actively proliferating cells and apparently quiescent cells. Occasionally, CTC clusters are also found associated with cells of the immune system, and our RNA sequencing data revealed that these are most likely tumor-associated macrophages. This finding supports the increasingly appreciated role played by tumor-associated macrophages in cancer progression [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . The fact that such tissue-derived macrophages travel with CTC clusters in the bloodstream has implications for the ability to noninvasively monitor tumor-immune cell interactions, a potentially important benefit given the increasing use of immune checkpoint blockade in the treatment of multiple types of cancer [CITATION_3] .",
